<hl>
<seg id=1> The Philippines accuses Malaysia attempting to seize Philippine islands and reefs </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Correspondent in Manila Fernand reports </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The Philippine official thinks Malaysia poses another potential threat in the Nansha Islands to the Philippines besides China. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> A document from the Philippine defense information bureau shows that Malay troops attempted to take seize one of the reefs belongs to the Philippine territory on one time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It says that, Malaysia's action to seize this reef may impose threat to the security of the Philippines, for the reef is near the Balawan Island of the Philippines geographically. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The document does not indicate when the incident took place, neither why the attempt of the Malay troops did not succeed. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Philippine defense officials told reporters earlier that, Malaysia's attempt took place in August, or several months before the Chinese navy's activities on the Mischief Reef found by the Philippines in November. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> They explained that, the Philippine government timely "convinced" and stopped Malaysia to conduct such program in that region. But the defense source of the Philippines refused to give details. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Before the Philippine military leaked Malaysia's attempt to seize Philippine-owned reefs, Philippine President Estrada refused the suggestion proposed by Philippine military to take control of the Philippine-owned reefs. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> In the same report, the Philippine military calls the facilities on the Mischief Reef built by the China a kind of "springboard", which prepared for the ultimate seisure of the nearby Reed Shaol and exploit oil resources there. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
